04770nam a22007215i 9781477313619DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212017txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017020579  a97814773136197 a10.7560/3135962doi  a(DE-B1597)587429  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aPN1992.8.H64bH56 2017 4aPN1992.8.H64bH56 2017 7aPER0100302bisacsh04a791.45/6532231 aHimberg, Julia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe New Gay for Pay :bThe Sexual Politics of American Television Production /cJulia Himberg. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2017  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The New Gay for Pay -- tCHAPTER 1 Visibility: Lesbian Programming and the Changing Landscape of Cable Television -- tCHAPTER 2 Advocacy: Hitching Activism to Modern Family ’s Gay Wedding -- tCHAPTER 3 Diversity: Under-the- Radar Activism and the Crafting of Sexual Identities -- tCHAPTER 3 Diversity: Under-the- Radar Activism and the Crafting of Sexual Identities -- tConclusion: The Personal Is Still Political (and Profitable) -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTelevision conveys powerful messages about sexual identities, and popular shows such as Will & Grace, Ellen, Glee, Modern Family, and The Fosters are often credited with building support for gay rights, including marriage equality. At the same time, however, many dismiss TV’s portrayal of LGBT characters and issues as “gay for pay”—that is, apolitical and exploitative programming created simply for profit. In The New Gay for Pay, Julia Himberg moves beyond both of these positions to investigate the complex and multifaceted ways that television production participates in constructing sexuality, sexual identities and communities, and sexual politics. Himberg examines the production stories behind explicitly LGBT narratives and characters, studying how industry workers themselves negotiate processes of TV development, production, marketing, and distribution. She interviews workers whose views are rarely heard, including market researchers, public relations experts, media advocacy workers, political campaigners designing strategies for TV messaging, and corporate social responsibility department officers, as well as network executives and producers. Thoroughly analyzing their comments in the light of four key issues—visibility, advocacy, diversity, and equality—Himberg reveals how the practices and belief systems of industry workers generate the conceptions of LGBT sexuality and political change that are portrayed on television. This original approach complicates and broadens our notions about who makes media; how those practitioners operate within media conglomerates; and, perhaps most important, how they contribute to commonsense ideas about sexuality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aGender identity on television. 0aHomosexuality and televisionzUnited States. 0aHomosexuality and television-United States. 0aHomosexuality on television. 0aTelevision and gayszUnited States. 0aTelevision and gays-United States. 0aTelevision programsxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aTelevision programsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/31359640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477313619423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477313619/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles 